</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊢</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.936em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>means, but would understand if you explained it to them.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>#!@$!@%#, I'm no longer a mathematician...</p>",
        "id": 197455261,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1589394166
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110032\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/238830-Lean-for.20the.20curious.20mathematician.202020/topic/audience/near/197455087\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would suggest that a \"mathematician\" means something like: someone who doesn't know what</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊢</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi><mo>⊢</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>e</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\frac{\\Gamma, x : A \\vdash e : B}\n{\\Gamma \\vdash (\\lambda x, e) : A \\to B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:2.3074399999999997em;vertical-align:-0.936em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.3714399999999998em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊢</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">λ</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">e</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊢</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">e</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.936em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>means, but would understand if you explained it to them.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I guess your definition is broad, it includes many working programmers who essentially do constructive mathematics all day, but they don't use algebra or analysis<br>\nDid you mean to catch those people?</p>",
        "id": 197455474,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394280
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm, I didn't really intend to</p>",
        "id": 197455502,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589394294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Proposal: We're aiming at \"mathematicians\", where a \"mathematician\" is someone who could contribute to mathlib without having to learn new math, but may still need to learn Lean</p>",
        "id": 197455549,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does that seem right?</p>",
        "id": 197455559,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394329
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess I was assuming that the original conference was mostly not aimed at undergrads, if only because for the most part undergrads don't travel to such conferences.</p>",
        "id": 197455699,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589394387
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I went to <a href=\"http://www.qciao.org/home/belfastoct2016\">a conference like this</a> as an undergrad</p>",
        "id": 197455738,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>where \"like this\" means \"teach the basics of some theorem-proving field, and have some informal research conversations on the side\"</p>",
        "id": 197455773,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394431
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So my mental picture of a \"mathematician\" was more like a grad student/postdoc/faculty.</p>",
        "id": 197455775,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589394433
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The hardest part was getting funding (Caltech has a general fund for undergrad academic travel, but I assume at most schools funding is harder to access), so I think you'd see more undergrads for things like this which are free.<br>\n(It kind of sucked to skip a week of class, but not that much? I guess some undergrads care about getting good grades for some reason)</p>",
        "id": 197455851,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394482
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course, being online the event now has an entirely different set of constraints so that may not be a reasonable assumption</p>",
        "id": 197455890,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589394484
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>also undergrads are looking for things to do because school now _sucks_ compared to school four months ago</p>",
        "id": 197456235,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394674
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i know plenty who are just taking time off next semester to read books or do research on their own</p>",
        "id": 197456271,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394694
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(if you have spare funding and want a research assistant, undergrads are \"on sale\" right now)</p>",
        "id": 197456381,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589394738
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I agree it would be great to have some kind of an event targeted at bored undergrads (or high school students). I don't know whether a single event can reasonably target a range that also includes \"mathematicians\"; maybe it can. At a minimum, I think it needs to be advertised differently.</p>",
        "id": 197457970,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589395389
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>right</p>",
        "id": 197458009,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395416
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>my only point is that any reasonable definition of \"mathematician\" includes some people who are still undergrads</p>",
        "id": 197458038,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395432
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>like, it should include all people who write serious papers that prove new theorems and post them to arxiv, right?</p>",
        "id": 197458101,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395449
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i think i've seen the phrase \"grad students and advanced undergrads\" used for things like this before</p>",
        "id": 197458178,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395490
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There aren't many undergrads in that category, and those that are know what they are getting into</p>",
        "id": 197458234,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1589395517
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah, I agree you don't need special advertising for them</p>",
        "id": 197458269,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395536
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I brought this up only for helping define the set of people we're after</p>",
        "id": 197458293,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395548
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and to point out that \"has enrolled in a PhD program\" is not true for all of the people we're after</p>",
        "id": 197458384,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Basically, I'm imagining that it is centered somewhere around \"postdocs\", and has a small enough radius to be manageable, whatever that means.</p>",
        "id": 197458426,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589395598
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course not all, but maybe like 80%.</p>",
        "id": 197458438,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589395603
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe 80% is too high, I don't know.</p>",
        "id": 197458458,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589395615
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i'm imagining the center is more like second-year grad students</p>",
        "id": 197458464,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because postdocs need to write papers that prove new theorems to get jobs</p>",
        "id": 197458488,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395628
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>at least this is the case in TCS (=theoretical computer science, the theorem-proving community i'm most familiar with, people who prove things about complexity classes and quantum computers and fourier analysis on the boolean cube)</p>",
        "id": 197458503,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1589395638
    }
]